context: The late Georgian period saw the birth of <b8_0>the semi-detached house<b8_0/>, planned systematically, as a suburban compromise between the terraced houses of the city and the <b5_0>detached "villas<b5_0/>" further out, where land was cheaper. There had been occasional examples in town centres going back to medieval times. Most early suburban examples are large, and in what are now the outer fringes of Central London, but were then in areas being built up for the first time. <a0_0><b4_0>Blackheath, Chalk Farm<b4_0/> and St John's Wood<a0_0/> are among the areas contesting being the original home of the semi. <a1_0>Sir John Summerson<a1_0/> gave primacy to the Eyre Estate of St John's Wood. A plan for this exists dated <a2_0>1794<a2_0/>, where "the <b6_0>whole development consists of pairs of semi-detached houses,<b6_0/> So far as I know, this is the first recorded scheme of the kind". In fact <a3_0>the <b7_0>French Wars<b7_0/><a3_0/> put an end to this scheme, but when the development was finally built it retained the semi-detached form, "a revolution of striking significance and far-reaching effect".
